{"actual_usd":0.15619,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":196,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—Christians aren't saying there are three separate beings who all happen to be gods.\" *I rub my thumb along the worn edge of my Bible and glance up at the bright square, where the morning light is catching on the well chain.* \"We're saying one God, and within the one divine being, three persons: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.\"\n\n\"It's a hard doctrine because it guards two truths at once.\" *I lift one hand a little, as if balancing weight in the air.* \"The Father is God. The Son is God. The Spirit is God. And yet the Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father. Not three gods—because not three separate divine beings. One God. Three persons.\"\n\n\"If you like, we can take the slow road through why the church ended up saying it that way at all—mostly because Scripture kept forcing both halves on them at once.\"","rolling_24h_usd":38.01271500000002,"run_id":"bb8d8d03-1597-4e92-a5d7-6608a6fb2db8"}
